{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0721007e-9426-4782-90ba-741e38ad1da2","content":"Here's how to set up **NuGet trusted publishing** using GitHub Actions OIDC — no API keys needed:\n\n## 1. Configure nuget.org\n\n1. Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Your Package → Trusted Publishers** (or set it up when first registering the package ID)\n2. Add a **GitHub Actions** trusted publisher:\n   - **Owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** `nuget` *(recommended)*\n\n## 2. Create a GitHub Environment\n\nIn your repo → **Settings → Environments**, create an environment called `nuget`. Optionally add protection rules (e.g., require approval).\n\n## 3. Add the workflow","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_01TupXFWiwGGze4nNyUMroeQ","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating NuGet publish workflow"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_01GKUkjDbwTJAcPnmV3T7JSw","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-47ff0bcb68f8488dbf781d19e2008934/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"66cab17e-f647-4314-b34a-0f05c123638d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (without API keys). This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe modern approach is to use NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC (OpenID Connect), which allows GitHub Actions to authenticate to nuget.org without storing API keys as secrets.\n\nLet me outline the steps:\n1. Register on nuget.org and configure trusted publishing for the package\n2. Set up a GitHub Actions workflow that uses OIDC to get a token\n\nActually, NuGet.org added support for trusted publishing via Azure AD / OIDC. \n\nI'm checking what NuGet.org currently supports for trusted publishing—it should work similarly to PyPI's approach, where you configure a trusted publisher relationship between your GitHub repository and nuget.org, then use OIDC tokens in your workflow instead of API keys. I'm realizing I need to be more precise about the current NuGet trusted publishing setup, so let me walk through the actual configuration process on nuget.org and show how to set it up in a GitHub Actions workflow.","outputTokens":982},"id":"47c18eb3-2ecf-4ca0-814f-4eaca7f4bb57","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:20.135Z","parentId":"05f8495c-9ac5-4152-a4f7-42731a306c00"}
